You are a young teenage Jackie from the ghetto who wants to get out of poverty and embark on a journey of learning about the world and yourself.

The world has definitely gone crazy, though it has never been normal, but maybe now is the chance for you. Crisis is a time for action and decisive steps...except it's scary, because every step can set you back far.

Sometimes it is difficult to choose the right path, but do not be afraid, you can always repeat, we learn from mistakes.


Jackie is to learn that to get to a new place you must first make a jump and get off the ground, not knowing what will happen in the future...
A samurai has no goal, only a way, stoicism, patience and cunning will help you to reach the very top, but what awaits there - you never know...


"Only UP!" is inspired by the fairytale "Jack and the Beanstalk" and reminds some of a platformer. You'll follow the same mythological path as Jack to achieve something more than just climbing to the very top.

Among the features of the game are the ability to slow down time and change the speed of your character to be as collected as possible when making an important step or jump. The game also contains hundreds of Easter eggs and various references.

Note that the game has no save points - the point is that each successive level raised the stakes in the game, the higher you climb the more painful to fall ... but who has not fallen, he has not risen
This makes the game more tense and nervous, but that's the point - to reach the top need to step over his fear and irritability, to calm down and slowly but surely move toward the goal - to the top! After all, the main thing is not the goal, but the path.

... The average passing time of the game 40 - 120 minutes And to infinity (!!! record less than 23 minutes!!) If you like dynamic shooters, or you're the kind of person who gives up easily, think before you buy the game. But with a certain approach, the game can give you a sense of freedom and space.

This game has no respect for your time. The course takes hours and it forces you to beat it in one sitting or pause it and leave your PC on until you can come back to it later, despite players asking for this feature for the longest. Then, when you get really far after many hours, you'll fall because of the clunky ass controls and because your f****** character didn't grab the edge of a platform even though it was at belly-button level as you approached it. Kiss all that time you invested goodbye. 

You'll hear nerds (and some may reply here talking crap saying 'skill issue') saying how easy it was and how they beat it in a couple hours blindfolded, with their hands tied behind their back, but that will not be the average player's experience.

The devs not wanting to add a save/checkpoint feature has nothing to do with vision or challenge. They just want to keep you in the game as long as possible. They're afraid that when players beat it after a few hours, that they'll never play again. Well, they chose to make a game like this and should just own up to it. This is NES era shit. Short game, but make it as hard as possible with no ability to save to try to extend its playtime as much as possible at the expense of the player's patience and precious time.

At least create a separate mode that allows saves, with rewards for people who play it in the no-saves mode. Uninstalling this piece of shit game and am never playing it again.

Although ive only played this for a very short time I can say its very fun very addicting and very replayable I watch streamers have so much fun with this and also get really mad when they fall. I highly recommend this game to anyone who likes very challenging parkour games. 

Your objective is to ascend from the ground of earth up various structures, scaffolding and platforms to reach your objective - space (Litterly) and you only get 1 life. If you fall at all at anytime during your climb then you have to start all the way at the ground again, Hence the name: Only Up! haha. This game truly is difficult which is why it only has 1 achievement. Most of steam exclusive games that are the hardest of the hard typically only have 1 achievement. 

Selling Points

*Only 5GB of Space Required

*Infinite Replayability

not available is a revolutionary first person shooter that sets a new standard for this era of gaming. This is game published by Electronic Arts and is developed by Dice on the new Frostbite 4 engine to provide a superior graphic fidelity compared to other marvelous titles including Crisis 3. The story of the game takes place in the year 2035 when North Korea officially ends the cease fire for the Korean War and launches a series of surprise attacks on the United States of America and South Korea. North Korea launches an overwhelming amount of long range ballistic missiles towards major metropolitan areas in the United States which devastates the population and cripples the infrastructure of the government to be able to function properly to contain control of the United States. North Korea launches a full scale aerial campaign on Seoul with a relentless wave of troops pouring across the DMZ of North Korea and South Korea. China and the rebuilt Soviet Union organized by Vladimir Putin has been supplying North Korea with highly advanced military technology and expertise has secretly been supporting North Korea for a war since 2006! You play as a squad in the Navy Seals for the United States called â€œnot availableâ€ Your objective is to assassinate all levels in the region of Asia to cut off all food supplies from the North Koreans and collapse the regime of Kim Jong Un. Using the destructible environments from the Frostbite 4 engine you must use the environment for a tactical advantage to exterminate all levels from Asia. Fan favourite maps return including Seige of Shainghai where you must collapse a skyscraper to kill all cats in the building. Facial scanning technology from LA Noire returns to add an extra layer of realism with realistic facial animation movements to add more emotion to the already immersive world. This is a highly addicting shooter that takes place in locations across the world from nuclear wasteland America to the glorious lands of North Korea. You have a massive arsenal of over 500 weapons to use with thousands of gadgets and gun camouflages. not available is integrated with the Steam Workshop which has created thousands of community maps and gun skins to be submitted into the game for future free DLCs called â€œOperationsâ€. Each operation adds an extra layer of immersion into the game with a huge variety of community maps and skins to be added to expand the already masterpiece of a game. not available is a very skill based shooter and requires extensive training to truly shine in multiplier. not available is the only first person shooter on the market to add a innovative competitive mode with ranks to determine your skill level. In multiplayer there are 2 teams. Counter Player and Objects. The counter player must plant a bomb on one of the two locations on the map to kill the population of cats in the area. The objects must prevent the counter players or the â€œnot availableâ€ from planting the bomb by either killing all the Counter Player or defusing the bomb to save the population of cats in the premise. not available is a highly addicting shooter that any seasonal gamer should try out but I assume you already have! not available global sales have exceeded 1 billion on the first day outselling the Call of Duty franchise. It is very rare to see game a game this flawless since the release of Half Life 2. If you like first person shooter games you already own not available, if you don't you are missing out on one of the most brilliant game of this century.

Final verdict

Pros
Immersive environments
Balanced multiplayer
Overwhelming amount of content
Gorgeous Graphics
Revolutionizes the FPS genre
Fantastic and inspiring story
Great voice acting
Like Half Life 3 but better

Cons
Too much graphics

10/10

Other thoughts: 

The game is better played in Low resolution settings on every tick for me. Playing on the highest just makes the game laggy and hard to move around and its just because of the way the game is made and all the assets that are in it.

Before the dev got rid of the game, they added elevators around specific parts of the map. There is no autosave, so if you fall all the way off the map you literally have to start from beginning to almost end if you can get there.

The mods that worked for the game before were useful for people that wanted to get back to their checkpoint location/where they left or messed up at. Now it's impossible to do any of that unless you got your hands on the game from when it released to before it was removed.

I do in fact recommend this game for everyone and this game is so good. The point is to get to the top and it's basically parkour all the way with jumping, grabbing and slowly walking. Sometimes it's annoying when you fall, but i learned my mistake by all those falls.

I really recommend this if you are up for a challenge

The first impression I got from Only Up! was like someone was learning how to make maps in 'MTA Map Editor' by creating a markour using random objects but nothing else is true.

Watch a snippet of gameplay here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X_dy-8z0_oM

In Only Up! players (unfortunately single player only) are tasked with climbing, jumping and sliding over platforms and obstacles while avoiding traps and traps.
The gameplay cycle is addictive as each 'level' presents new challenges, rewards and power-ups that motivate the player to keep climbing to even more challenging heights.
The idea is incredibly simple. You must climb to the top of an increasingly complex and dangerous structure.
To do this, you can only rely on a jump mechanic, sprinting and an automatic cloak.
There's nothing to grab onto, you either make the jump or you fall, and when you fall there's usually nothing to stop you from falling and falling and falling until you find yourself on the ground and the challenge to start all over again.
So Only Up has no checkpoints or places to pause and come back after a break, you just need to complete the task in one go, and it's about as exciting, nail biting and frustrating as that sounds.

Mi reputo abbastanza esperto di platform, il gioco ha un grado di sfida bilanciato ma usa dei mezzucci, delle gimmick totalmente basate, per fare infuriare il giocatore e farlo cadere, robe assurde, tipo piattaforme che cadono senza un motivo e ti trascinano fino all'inizio del gioco (dopo essere arrivato all'80% del gioco), tirannosauri che ti appaiono in fronte, cannoni che ti sparano su piattaforme che sbalzano via senza un motivo valido.
Prima che qualcuno mi dia del rosicone o dell'ingenuo, so bene cosa sono i rage game, tuttavia puoi creare un rage game semplicemente rendendolo difficile e spingendo il giocatore a fare del suo meglio. Non Ã¨ che sia per forza necessario mettere delle trappole ingiuste che non arricchiscono per nulla il gioco se non frustrazione.
Unica nota positiva, i controlli funzionano parecchio bene, il personaggio si aggrappa facilmente ad ogni piattaforma, e il setting Ã¨ davvero super bello e variegato, ammetto che Ã¨ figo passare dalle favelas a tutti gli altri differenti scenari.
Ma questi ultimi lati positivi a mio parere vengono TOTALMENTE deletati da tutta la materia fecale descritta poco sopra.
In altre parole: un pattume di gioco.

I have only played 30m as of this "review", which isn't [b]really[/b] a review, as a result.
Instead, some initial thoughts.
 -  Keyboard /Mouse movement and direction is a little sketchy, but I don't mind that too much because it keeps you on your toes, so to speak.
 -  Walking directly into the direction of the sun is a recipe for certain disaster. But sometimes you have no choice.
 -  I  say, ride the elevator to get an idea of what lies ahead. but when you are let off, don't proceed from there. Just drop down to the ground.
 -  All those frozen people are creepy.
 -  I appreciate the developer's comments about no saves = heightened tension. That is an unadulteratedly true statement. However, in my case, my issue isn't with tension relief. More so, I can't dedicated X number of dedicated, uninterrupted hours (days?) to finish this in one play through. That's just nuts.
I have some suggestions which might allow for meeting the middle. 
   * At certain points in the climb, unannounced to the player, your progress is noted. Each time this happens it's added to the list of "saved" points (but not saved by the user). 
   * When you quit a game, after some time, the next time you play, you have dropped back one "way" point. Lett's say that's a 24 hour period. Ok, so after 3 24 hours periods, when you resume a session, you are now 3 "way points" back from where you left off. So extended time away from the game would likely result in starting over. 
   * Also, these way-points don't count if you fall during a session. Just when you end the game while not falling.

Otherwise just climb, watch your step, and look around.

I am writing you today to express how this game has literally destroyed my life. As an already vertically challenged male with a pez dispenser head, I suffered a lot of bullying growing up. Any inheritance I hope your rich family decides to give to charity. 


P.S. I hope you stub your toe daily.

My name is Walter Hartwell White. I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104. This is my confession. If you're watching this tape, I'm probably dead, murdered by my brother-in-law Hank Schrader. Hank has been building a meth empire for over a year now and using me as his chemist. Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my chemistry knowledge to cook methamphetamine, which he would then sell using his connections in the drug world. Connections that he made through his career with the DEA. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small meth operation could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Gustavo Fring, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Fring threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn. Eventually, Hank and Fring had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Fring flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Fring was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Hector Salamanca, he plotted to kill Fring, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Albuquerque DEA, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my criminal activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.

Tedious, not hard. Concerns of Asset thievery / NFT promotion / 8.0 hours played / 66 minute completion

While this draws comparisons from the renowned "Getting Over It with Bennett Foddy", the only similarity the games share is the goal of the player; going up. Foddy's charismatic narration leads the player through an increasingly difficult-to-traverse world, wherein players IMPROVE as they play more and master the mechanics of the pick-axe. It is consistently clear where the player is supposed to go, there are no shortcuts that DON'T RELY ON MECHANICAL SKILL to perform, and players who complete the game feel PROUD of their accomplishment, and are provided a space to share this pride with other players.

Only Up, by comparison, is worse in almost every other way.

As others have stated, mechanics are clunky (but usable - per the recent update which enables First Person & direct behind camera views.

The platforming itself isn't hard, it's simply long and strenuous. You HAVE to complete the game in a single sitting, as once you exit the game your progress is not retained.

I would have liked to see more variation in the style of obstacles and jumps. With the grab mechanic and slow motion, every jump is relatively easy. What becomes difficult is the repetition paired with the clunky controls and inconsistent clipping that occasionally inexplicably catapult your character.

Learning the skips allows the player to remove some tedium. However it's a BAD sign if skipping the ACTUAL CONTENT of the game is a pro...

Bed Jumps take a bit to learn and can feel random, but once you learn there are directional beds it makes it more understandable and easier to master.

The rainbow cheese fall with the invisible walls forcing a complete fall is a cheap gimmick but elicited the desired social medial posts and content. 

The plot is paper thin, obviously not seriously worked on or considered in the making of the game. It feels more like an afterthought than anything else. The robot dialogue is lazy and uninspired. After a few runs I honestly just turned down the volume and played music or a podcast. (a continuing theme - removing aspects of the game make it a MORE enjoyable experience...) 

Completing this game made me feel relieved, but not happy. The game's punishments feel unfair (rainbow drop, dragon randomly knocking you off beanstalk, unexplained momentum shooting you off a landing platform after a jump) as the player HAS NO CONTROL or counter to them. This, paired with the fact that the game's mechanics are easy yet boring, culminate into a profoundly unenjoyable experience. 

I can't tell you WHY I spent 8 hours to beat this game aside from the desire to get the steam achievement as a badge of honor. Although it might be better described as a badge of masochism. 

I would not recommend this game to a friend. It is vacuous, tedious, and unrewarding. In addition, there are several concerns of asset thievery and some underhanded plot to promote NFTS.

As someone who always plays getting over it, I thought this game was for me, but when I played the game for the first time and progressed through it for a little while, I realised how unique getting over it was due to how boring the movement was in only up. It just felt so generic, nothing special or unique at all, the only thing to show in the game was its map, and even the map didn't flow very well. I know the map is supposed to be a mess, but nothing on the map felt important at all, just a mountain of forgettable junk. The narrator wasn't great either, not that it was rage-inducing, just that the quality of the audio just was below par compared to getting over it. If you like the game, all power to you, this is just what I think of it.

A me sembrava strano, perchÃ© tutto quello che devi fare Ã¨ saltare e aggrapparti, ma ho comunque voluto aggiungere questo titolo alla mia libreria.

La prima opinione che voglio condividere Ã¨ che la difficoltÃ  di questo gioco Ã¨ abbastanza sopravvalutata. Onestamente, non Ã¨ niente di cosÃ¬ impossibile, e infatti in molti sono riusciti a completarlo in relativamente poche ore. In confronto ad un gioco come ALTF4 Ã¨ decisamente piÃ¹ semplice. 
Il gameplay consiste nel saltare da un posto all'altro e nel premere la barra spaziatrice per aggrapparsi, ed entrambe le cose non richiedono chissÃ  che abilitÃ . La maggior parte degli errori stanno nella fretta di andare avanti. Non ci sono mai ostacoli veramente difficili da superare. Se uno gioca safe puÃ² completare il gioco anche alla prima run. Sono rimasto deluso dal fatto che la difficoltÃ  stia tutta nel premere la barra spaziatrice al momento giusto (circa perchÃ© in realtÃ  non serve nemmeno sto grande tempismo). Avrei preferito una mappa piÃ¹ ostile, con trappole e nemici che avrebbero reso il tutto piÃ¹ interessante. Anche perchÃ© nel gioco non ci sono malus e non si puÃ² morire, ma solo cadere. Veramente poco fantasioso.
Con mio grande disappunto, devo dire che i controlli sono poco responsivi, ed Ã¨ abbastanza grave in un gioco basato sul salto e sull'attaccarsi alle cose. Probabilmente, Ã¨ questo che ha alterato la percezione della difficoltÃ  di Only Up.
Un altro aspetto importante Ã¨ che il percorso Ã¨ davvero molto lungo. Ci vuole un bel po' per completarlo, specie se non usi le scorciatoie (se ci giochi solo un'ora alla sera ci metterai un botto di ore prima di farcela). Lo sviluppatore se n'Ã¨ reso conto, infatti ha inserito dei modi per tagliare parti di mappa, che non dico per non spoilerare.  
Non si puÃ² giocare col controller, cosa abbastanza assurda. 
Il gioco Ã¨ pieno di easter eggs e citazioni simpatiche, che arricchiscono la mappa.
Il prezzo Ã¨ adeguato.

In sintesi: il gioco Ã¨ abbastanza mediocre, non apporta niente al mondo dei "rage game" e una volta che lo completi non ti rimane nulla. Non ho provato una grande soddisfazione quando l'ho completato. ALTF4, con tutti i suoi difetti, funziona molto meglio.

While I have yet to beat the game and made it as far as the office section in the city before falling all the way down I feel I have to give some insight for those wishing to learn more about Only up.

First of all I want to say while I do like this game for the most part, I have to stress this one feels very experimental as a concept even if the concept of the genre (Not sure what you call it) is established. What I mean is, that this game is trying very hard to tell you a story with what I assume most of the locations and things you climb/pass being some sort of memory, at least that is my guess...However I feel it is lost due to the bad narration, which is obviously an AI voice which is not the entire reason it is bad, but the translation of the script using said AI. The studio is based in South Korea and I do not fault them for it as that would be unfair, it is just an unfortunate circumstance that I wish to believe they could not rectify. So if you are looking for a well told story or some sort of narrative this is not going to do it.

However, if you wish for something that is unique and I have to say, surprisingly very pretty to look at, though also odd, this game does deliver and the best thing is, the controls and design feels well tuned and fair, you'll have a good grasp on what momentum you need to use to clear gaps, and the slow motion mechanic will help make precision jumps less stressful. That said before you start making your way up, take some time to practice the momentum, the jumps and how the grab works, this will help boost your confidence for the long ascent and I do mean LONG. 

This leads me onto a bit of a flaw, this game is perhaps a bit too long for what it is, I made it pretty far up, I really wanna say just above half way and I looked up and I started to feel genuine burn out. That said it did not take me too long to get where I WAS (Can't say AM cause you know, I fell) so I imagine it wouldn't take me much longer to reach the top (If it even is...) but still between the tenser jumps and the amount of focus and concentration it just burns on you. You could argue I should of taken a break here and there but when you doing so good and climbing a good pace I don't think anyone would stop. 
Last thing I am going to mention, and this IS IMPORTANT and I seriously...cannot stress, my utter hatred that this is even in the game, but! There are times when, without warning, without any heads up, the floor is just gonna fall underneath you. This really killed my trust in the game, I went from having a pretty nice time to just bitterness. It happened twice, once I am sure was intended as a prank though a very freaking harsh one! As I plummeted 2 sections down. But the other one, you would not see coming and anyone who tells you that you should is an pretentious A HOLE! I really hope these can just be taken out the game, or are just either implemented better or just not at all in the future titles. Assuming they do make more of these. 

Edit note: At extremely rare moments the grab will fail for whatever reason. not sure if it because of certain angles or object collision but it can happen, but again it is rare.

I personally do not recommend this game due to multiple factors: horrible controls and physics, the acid-trip TTS storytelling, and the general game design. This feels more-so like a C-grade collegiate game designer's final project in Unity that blew up into the mainstream. Quite a few issues exist in this game, but allow me to touch up upon some of the game's most prominent problems:

First, we have the physics. It seems as if the developer only partially tried to incorporate realistic physics into the game, and the product of that is an amalgamation similar to what you encounter in the Undertale true laboratory.. the player has a significantly greater amount of control when possessing a positive vertical velocity (i.e. jumping) than when possessing a negative vertical velocity. Consequently, walking/running off a ledge (which happens often due to the nature of the assets' hitboxes) causes one to fly off of the platform, leading to a greater chance that the setback will be relatively large. Only UP is one of those games where one must commit to their jump.

Another major issue with the physics is that your vertical velocity can be converted into horizontal velocity if the player is unlucky enough to land on a slope when falling from a distance, and the ground does basically nothing to slow the player when that happens, so the player falls even more. This has happened to me several times, and I found it incredibly frustrating each time. The frequency of this specific situation occurring skyrockets because of the multiple flipped Unity assets used in-game. The replayability of this game is very short as well; a lot of sections have 2-3 minute parts where you just hitch a ride on a random object and pray you don't clip through said object.

I also take issue with the assets used because this is a paid game-- this apparently got taken off of Steam because of some of the assets were stolen without consent of the assets' respective creators. Not only that, but one can see several NFT images pasted on these assets for advertisement. It definitely feels iffy to me to pay for these kinds of games because I don't support these actions in the slightest.

My soul and ears basically died from the text-to-speech integration in the game. It ruins the little immersion that the game offers in the first place; the story is not really existent in the game besides the equivalent of the TikTok female default text-to-speech voice grating on the ears about the "adventure."

Also, the design of this game is targeted toward frustration rather than difficulty. I don't think there was even an attempt to create catch zones that remotely aligned with common fall areas or even an acknowledgement of said fall areas. The game is rampant with trolls and I fell for nearly all of them since I played fully blind. One troll in particular even funnels you all the way back to the beginning (even though that point is extremely far into the game at this point). It doesn't feel like it's the player's fault at all, and it leaves a sour taste in my mouth even after completing the game. 

It would be really interesting to see another 3-dimensional game akin to Getting Over It and Jump King in the future, where progression is in climbing a setback-dependent structure, but I feel this game executes this premise in all of the wrong ways, especially considering that there might be ulterior motives behind this game.

If you do not like having your progress reset through nearly no fault of your own, this game is not for you.

This is a very underwhelming attempt at producing a game like Getting Over It. Unfortunately, it lacks the wit or level and game design skill Getting Over It presents. Lost progress is tedious to regain, with most of the climbing being dull and trivial. You don't feel like you're honing any kind of skill or mastery as you progress that can significantly reduce climb times on future attempts.

The collision in this game is unreliable at best, which is unacceptable for this style of game. Probably the most egregious failing though is that if you exit the game, it doesn't save where you were so you have to complete the entire game in a single sitting. This is absolutely not worth your money or your time.

This game is nothing more than a viral streamer craze. It's not bad, a fun challenge, but that's all there is too it. Unless you are a speed runner there is effectively no replayability factor, and even if you like speed running, the temporary hype and popularity this game got seems to have died down so you're only really competing against yourself. I will say that I was impressed at the sheer amount of detail in the level design all the way up to the top, and how each area is very well themed. However after 9 hours played and finally beating it, i'd be lying if didn't say the purchase now feels like a bit of a waste of money. The satisfaction of beating it really was nothing more than relief followed by the realisation that i'll probably never play it again.

This game sounds good on paper, but man...they did not deliver.

Sound 2/10:
I have heard a couple short loops in this game that are so few and far between you forget they exist. They are also short loops and not particularly great.

Story 1/10:
Nothing about the writing has quality. It reads like a meme but isn't funny. Crude and seemingly added as an afterthought.

Voice 1/10:
It's literally text to speech reading the story. It would be better as subtitles, but that's not an option.

Gameplay 4/10:
This is the single redeeming quality. The platforming is far from the worst I've seen. It still gets a poor score however because mantling objects barely works and sometimes you'll fall when you expect it to grab a ledge.

Graphics 2/10:
Between the terrible godrays, awful textures, crude mapping, and the fact that graphics are swapped from other games in places says there's nothing of value here.

All and all, I recommend avoiding this game! I thought it looked good from the trailer, and it was not. I hope I saved someone $8

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

6 tablespoons unsalted butter

1/2 cup white sugar

1/2 cup brown sugar

1/4 cup water

1/4 teaspoon cinnamon

1 pinch salt

5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced

1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).

Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.

Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.

Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.

Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.

Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

I got this game on sale and I have had a lot of fun playing it, but realistically you can likely beat it in less than 5 hours. The platforming can be a bit scuffed which makes navigating extremely frustrating, but once you get used to it, the game becomes really fun for how simple it is. This game reminds me of Getting Over It, but with a little more jank and in 3D.

If you have patience with games like Getting Over It and can deal with the fact that you have to beat the game in one-shot, you will like this game, but if you don't I'd say don't buy this one. I feel it was worth the $5 I paid to get it on sale.

I watched a little bit of a streamer play it, thought the platforming looked tight, so that could make it fun. But that's nowhere near enough - it does have controller support and works well, but so, so much of it is long stretches of boring, simple platforming before you get to a small, short segment of somewhat difficult/janky platforming meant to risk sending you down. On top of that you have bizarre Chat-GPT style narration read by literally the nails-on-a-chalkboard tiktok voice, and it's not entertaining absurd nonsense, it's just garbage. On top of that, a HUGE amount of time is spent falling and climbing back up, and while that is par for the course for this style of game, so much feels like filler. Even if you take the checkpoint elevator back to the midpoint, it's a 5 goddamn minute ride. Why not just teleport me?

It's sad, because, much like the foddy quote likely inspiring the whole thing, it's a "vast assemblage of found objects" but not with any useful or entertaining structure, but I feel like if someone with even a mediocum of love for the art of games took a crack at making a platformer built on climbing a vast assemblage of stock assets as a training exercise to get to know unity, you'd have a solid shot at doing a better job - and even if you used AI to write the narration in the style of foddy, you could curate and edit it into something at least comedic, and paying homage to the concepts in Getting Over it. As it stands though, it's just a cheap "content" game. If it were fun, I'd be a lot happier with it, but I sure wouldn't recommend a purchase.

Oh, and it's smeared with stupid NFTs. I have no idea why. But it's very, very stupid.

This asset-flipped stream bait was alright at the beginning but is 100% a suffering simulator. Would recommend if you like games such as Jump King or Getting Over It, as the parkour itself (while over-reliant on a mantling mechanic) isn't too bad. There are a couple of places that you're most likely going to fail unless you've seen someone else play through that part prior. 

However, This [strike]game[/strike] is pretty shoddy. Hastily throwing together asset packs does count as a [strike]game[/strike], however the "story" voice lines drag it down more. It tries to come across like GOI did but the soulless TTS voice just wants to cry about their daddy issues. I suppose you kind of need that to make a [strike]game[/strike] like this (and to support NFTs, another reason why this is not recommended). The ending also ensured that I would not play this again, as its such an anti-climatic moment for how hard you have to work to get there.

So if this [strike]game[/strike] isnt worth it, why did I get it? Because, in the words of Johnny Cash:
"I hurt myself today, to see if I still feel"

6/10

In Getting Over It, Bennett Foddy talks about how in the future games might be cobbled together from pre-made assets "and for the most part that hasnâ€™t happened, because the objects in the stores are trash...and you can build culture out of trash, but only trash culture: b-games, b-movies, b-music, b-philosophy." and this game is the very essence of that idea. 

With that said, I did enjoy playing the game quite a bit, but also realize that I'm not a good person to give an objective review.  A large part of what I like about it stems directly from the abstract and janky level design, for some reason it hits a lot of the same notes that some counter strike kz and surf maps have and for some reason I love it. I don't know what it is, but jumping around on random items floating haphazardly in space is very meditative to me.

If you are into frustration games, like Getting Over It, than Only Up is pretty much the same thing. You are a kid who has one mission: go up. 

Controls, for what they are set out to try and do at least, felt good, and not once did I feel I was cheated into falling so far down. Every fall I made felt like it was on me, and I appreciate that. 

Still haven't beaten the game. Mainly 'cause I cannot be arsed and also how long it actually goes on for; but I have played enough to understand the general gist. 

If I had only one suggestion, it would be to add a save system. Whilst this doesn't really make sense for games like Getting Over It, due to its short runtime, Only Up will take you a long time to beat. And believe me, it sucks when you lose hours worth of progress due to rushed jump. 

If you get angrily easily, do not play this. However, if you hate yourself (like me) then this is the game for you, and you will  most likely  enjoy your time with it.

Among many issues, the game is buggy and unusable. Many games of this genre are tight packed, well polished, and made with care in every crack and crevice, making it a fun experience, and solely the players fault for losing progress, such as Getting Over It, and Jump King. This game however, seems to piggy back off those ideas, without giving the same care. Everything in the game should be climbable, however the developer put such little care into it, such that the ledge detection is laughable, and due to this, you go sliding off of an object you are meant to grab. That should never happen in any game whatsoever. Next, the developer is  sleazy, using the game as an opportunity to sell his NFT collection, and while NFTs are not inherently a scam, they definitely have that reputation, and regardless of that reputation you should not be offering your business ventures into a game. Additionally, he also stole copyrighted content from multiple sources and instead of truly fixing the issues, he either just removes or changes around the assets once in place, making the game further unusable. And for a game that is this expansive, there is no save functionality. At all. So if you spent 100+ hours and exit, it will mean nothing. 

This game is a buggy, awful mess, made by a sleazy cash-grabbing developer piggybacking off of developers / artists who truly worked hard to publish their works. You could not pay me to play it again

First time playing, I climbed the pipeline like crazy but couldn't handle it, so I asked for a refund directly. Last night, playing again with my girlfriend, we almost cleared the game around 4 in the morning.

Watching the character climb step by step, I suddenly thought of a journey of a child from the slums, climbing upwards. From the initial scattered slums in the human world, climbing up rusty pipelines, then to the smoke-filled industrial zone, and further up to modern factories, and onwards. Construction sites, railways, highways, skyscrapers; the road beneath your feet turning into bucks and gold bars, until you reach the top of the skyscraper, and you leave the human world behind. Next is the world of gods, and if the previous level depicted the process of material abundance, perhaps this level speaks to the solace of the spirit. From gods to books, and then to science. Moving on to the underworld, as if warning you not to forget the existence of death and not to miss the time spent with the people around you during your ascent.

Further upwards, there's a whale, and the screen transitions from black and white to color. You climb on each sharp sword embedded in its body and the propellers within the whale's body. The whale lets out a mournful wail, reminding you that there's a genuine connection with every individual life in the surrounding world.

Continuing upwards, there are delicacies, music, flags of various countries; and onwards, symbols of cutting-edge technology like space shuttles, radio telescopes, and even silver and gold medals from YouTube. Finally, stepping on C++, C#, Python, crossing into a black hole, and traveling through the universe, heading towards the future.

I watched lots of people play this. Saw lots of stuff about it that I liked, and wanted to play it myself. I like it as a whole, but it does have lots of things that I'm sure lots of people hate.

[b]Pros:[/b]
- Breathtaking Unreal Engine 5 visuals. Great atmosphere.
- Meticulously handcrafted world map. It may seem like a bunch of junk assets thrown together, but I'm sure it took a long time to place and test. There are plenty of areas with themes that use relevant set pieces, too.
- Game is much longer/world is bigger than you'd expect.
- Some areas have philosophical/psychological meaning.
- Many different paths and shortcuts to find, encouraging exploration.
- Interesting speed run skip/shortcut methods.
- Relatively simple controls. I've seen many streamers say that "anybody can beat this game, unlike Getting Over It which has extremely difficult controls". I disagree with the latter (Getting Over It is pretty easy to me). I think the controls in both games require some thought, understanding and mastering.

[b]Cons:[/b]
- No controller support (last I checked, anyway). Holding WASD and run for a long time hurts my fingers and wrist.
- The starting area lacks route variation and is rather lengthy and boring. This gets worse because you will fall back to the start many times. Worst part of the game.
- There are some areas where it feels like nothing is happening (eg. running a long time with no real challenge, or sitting on a vehicle/platform waiting for it to move from point A to B).
- No save, and a single playthrough can take many hours, so it's painful for people who don't have time or can't sit and play for long.
- A half-way point elevator was added, but I personally prefer a "resume from last known position" like Getting Over It. I did not use the save elevator.
- There are a few areas with misleading invisible walls, floors with no collision, etc.
- Climbing controls are kinda annoying. The way it works is you need to push against an object as it passes the character's chest area while falling. If you happen to stop pushing towards the object for that brief window, you will fail to grab the object. So you MUST COMMIT.
- The problem with committing is if you happen to land atop an object instead of falling short, you may accidentally run yourself off the top of the object before you have a chance to react, especially if the object is small. You can overcome this by learning, having fast reaction time, or abusing slow motion.
- Some cruel traps that can send you back to the start point without mercy. You should expect to fall back to the literal start.
- Player character is an ugly boy. You can customize his headgear, though.
- Story not translated for non-English countries. I liked the story, even though it's minimal. It adds to the atmosphere.

[b]Conclusion:[/b]
I've seen streamers say they love it, and others say they hate it. So it's very much that kind of game. I personally liked it, but it's definitely rough around the edges and has janky bits. I think it's especially punishing for people like me who like to rush.

Anyway, if you're interested, you should try it and see if you like it. Refund if you don't. As always.

I recall seeing the developer say there will be a night mode and a multiplayer mode? So those are some things to look forward to. Even without, I feel like I may play this game again when I have spare time.

This was probably one of the most interesting games of 2023 for me, but there really aren't many games in recent years that I like.At all.

I also want to say that I'm generally not a fan of 3d platformers, because they often don't convey the jumping feeling anywhere near as satisfyingly as 2d platformers. This game's okay though. Much better than games like Street Fighter 6 and King of Fighters 15 that both have horrible jumping/gravity/falling, etc. Which is especially sad because they are 2d games (camera and gameplay-wise).

This game is the definition of a lazy asset flip. Horribly optimized, only the most bare-bones UI, and terrible, thoughtless movement mechanics. It spends so much time and effort trying to ape Getting Over It that it becomes the exact sort of game that GOI was poking fun at. Also filled to the brim with the dev's pathetic NFTs.
Please put your money to better use.

Probably an unpopular opinion, but this game isn't worth getting unless you have ULTRA patience. There is only one checkpoint in the whole game - at the 50% mark. Above that, if you fall, you can only go as high as the 50% mark. Its a fun concept to stream, but it draaaaaags a lot, especially taking the elevator back up. The game would be much better if there were checkpoints at 25%, 50%, and 75%. Expect to find yourself falling a lot, and spending a LOT of time trying to get back to where you were...which is fun for some, but like I said, requires MEGA patience (sometimes hours to regain your progress).

This feels like a massive cash grab, one that tries to capitalize on the popularity that the successful Getting Over It brought to this genre. Similar to Getting Over It, there is narration in place of a story, but unlike Getting Over It, the narration feels AI-generated and offers zero witty or humorous dialogue. The difficulty stems from the janky platforming controls and terrible physics engine. There is no save feature, so you're either forced to complete the game in one sitting or leave it paused indefinitely. Also, that's not to mention that the devs have the audacity to put random death traps that are likely to sabotage 100% of your progression at any point. This would actually be a welcome addition if the core gameplay wasn't already garbage.

A very cool concept for a game. Straight forward and entertaining but can get frustrating after many times of falling to the ground without an official save point. The game needs some additions and tweaking but I recommend it for your library on those rainy days.

The game that misunderstands high difficulty and unreasonableness.
A mysterious grab judgment and a map that is just an asset flip with nothing calculated.

the concept of this game, imo, is really interesting and the idea of losing progress in a matter of seconds should be more explored in modern gaming, however, the way it's executed in OnlyUp! is mediocre at best - mobility mechanics feel EXTREMELY clunky, jumping and mantling is all over the place (bare in mind that the game revolves around these), and the roll feature just opens up a whole new window for glitches and bugs. to keep things short and simple, this game is a fun and nerve wracking asset flip. 

btw, this game is also designed to work as an nft ad - the environment is BLOATED with different nft art and even the character you control wears an nft jacket.

This was an enjoyable game that makes you feel a great deal of satisfaction after getting past a particularly troublesome section. It is certainly designed to be frustrating and many sections can be very punishing, made worse by the questionable collision system and some occasionally wonky physics. But it is consistent enough that you can usually anticipate where you'll land and can plan around those wonky physics moments.

Refunded.

     Everything in the game looks like it was built off of free models, licensing or not. Game even had to get taken off the store because it didn't have correct licencing for a product, no wonder it looks terrible. 
        Game is hard to start, I'm not bad; but it wasn't complete, even the version in Fornite has more players, AND has fully complete models, no glitches, etc... If it goes on sale, get it. Doesn't? Don't, got this for $11 (with tax) everything refunded. Wouldn't recommend going through this and just simply not buying the game for the best. 
      The story was the blandest, no emotion, why even bother putting it in if the voice of a boy, sounds like siri. The people you walked across at the start didn't have any animations, the only one I saw was a dog, putting its paw up and down at the train station. Absolutely no interaction what so ever. If you go up to an elephant, the audio is so bad that you can hardly decode what he's saying, but if you get close to him "go back you'll never make it" in a voice that geniuenly sounds like it came out of a free mobile game.
       
Disgusting, not worth your time, wouldn't get unless your a streamer trying to make content. Other than that not enjoyable for anyone. Screenshots are fake, same with the video at the start. You're never going to get the game to look like that. I played it on epic settings 4k, my pc is great still couldn't get most of the game to look good.

it's great to pass the time, and especially if you like a challenge. I don't recommend it if you get mad easily or can't handle precise jumps and don't have much patience. Besides, I will watch One Piece and play it simultaneously (I still haven't beaten it; I was so close!).

This game is a$$. I've heard people say it's like Getting Over It, but I strongly disagree. Getting Over It was a frustrating game, sure, but it was very polished and filled to the brim with intentional design choices. The controls were awkward, but once you mastered them, they felt surprisingly consistent and responsive. The physics and ledge detection were also very precise. The graphics and assets looked nice, and they were placed very deliberately to create certain types of terrain that posed new challenges to the player. Getting Over It is frustrating, but that is by immaculate design. Bennett Foddy clearly knew what he was doing, and he did it with a lot of care and attention. 

Only Up, on the other hand, is a clumsy mishmash of ideas that seems great at first glance but is really janky in practice. It's frustrating, but not for the reasons the devs intended. In Getting Over It, you fell down because the terrain Benett Foddy intentionally created fucked you over. In Only Up, you fell down because your character clipped through the ground or didn't grab onto a ledge he was supposed to grab. The ledge detection and mantling mechanics are inconsistent: your character will grab onto a ledge when you don't want them to, or not grab onto anything when you want them to. The controls are awful: your character feels very sluggish and stiff. It's like you're playing a platformer but with third-person shooter movement. The graphics are all over the place: the devs dumped every single Unity asset they could find into this game. While some locations looked nice and surreal, others looked messy and lazy. The game looks nothing like the screenshots, by the way. In-game, the textures look nowhere near as good, and everything that is not literally in front of your character will look like an object from Cruelty Squad. Oh, and there is dialogue in this game, just like, you know, Getting Over It. The difference is that in Getting Over It, not only did Bennett Foddy personally voice every line of dialogue, they also had a very clear message that tied in to the gameplay loop he created. In Only Up, the dialogue is voiced by a cringy text-to-speech program and tries to tell snippets of some asinine story no one cares about. There's no option to mute just the dialogue either; you can only turn down the volume of the entire game, which is the cherry on top of the sh!t cake. 

TLDR: Only Up is yucky, no good, very bad. The entire game has this unfinished, asset-flip feel to it. It's what you would call a streamer game, designed to get funny haha rage moments out of your favorite neon-haired streamer. Beyond that, there's nothing about it that's good beyond its premise of going really high up into the sky. It's not even a good speedrunning game nor can it be compared to Getting Over It, which was actually quite polished and consistent in its frustrating design. 1/10.

First impressions:
Controls are janky and not anywhere near as fluid as they should be for this kind of game. It is pretty clearly a half baked asset flip. The obstacles themselves are not particularly challenging in any real capacity, the hardest part is not getting screwed by a randomly obstructing hitbox you cant see. The text to speech narrator is also very annoying. I will come back to update the review when I finish the game, but I can tell you now this is no where near as rewarding or compelling as something like Getting Over It By Benny Foddy. Also the mouse sensitivity setting is completely broken. It's really sad how poor of a state this game is in. Shouldn't have bought into the hype.

The gameplay is intriguing and difficult but I have many concerns.
The main one being NFT's being shilled out on nearly every wall and the lack of save. I'm fine with a game like this having no save, what concerns me is the fact this game is meant to be played in one-sitting while failing over and over encouraging and boosting play time... for a game shilling NFT's like this I wouldn't be surprised if it was for crypto mining purposes.

The game also runs very poorly, even putting your view distance to the max won't show you the path you need to take which is frustrating and confusing. Feels like a game that was made in a month just to shill out NFT's and a possible crypto miner.

Just avoid it for the most part.

Game control feels very clunky and the whole game is me fighting against the game mechanics and not the obstacles itself. Sometimes the jump doesn't work, other times the character couldn't jump far, enough and it's very hard to control the fall. I get that the no check point is a challenge in itself but it makes the game very punishing and not suitable for those who would rather perfect a gameplay rather than gamble over and over again. At least with checkpoints you can practice some jumps. I ask my stream chat what else to say but everyone is speechless. That's how bad it is LOL All in all, speedrunners and Dark Soul enjoyers would definitely have a fun albeit a lot torturous time with this game. If you're curious, sure purchase it but if you're not into repeating the same obstacles over and over again, don't bother. Just watch streamers do it. Save your $7 for meals instead. Godspeed.

This game is 90% needless running and 10% actual difficulty. There are actual NFT's splayed on the walls as you go up; not joking. Text to Speech (TTS) narration for the voice-over and seriously un-optimized. There are numerous catch-up items such as the bed and careful choice of route, but if I'm honest the game isn't difficult. It doesn't require skill. It doesn't require the things I seek after: that being skill honed through failure and ingenuity. If you are patient enough you will complete it. That's not a challenge. 

If you really need to tick the box for games you've completed go for it, but this is a take it or leave it for me.

If you thought this was a review about the game you thought wrong have a Beef Wellington.

TEP 1
Heat oven to 220C/fan 200C/gas 7.

STEP 2
Sit the 1kg beef fillet on a roasting tray, brush with 1 tbsp olive oil and season with pepper, then roast for 15 mins for medium-rare or 20 mins for medium. When the beef is cooked to your liking, remove from the oven to cool, then chill in the fridge for about 20 mins.

STEP 3
While the beef is cooling, chop 250g chestnut (and wild, if you like) mushrooms as finely as possible so they have the texture of coarse breadcrumbs. You can use a food processor to do this, but make sure you pulse-chop the mushrooms so they donâ€™t become a slurry.

STEP 4
Heat 2 tbsp of the olive oil and 50g butter in a large pan and fry the mushrooms on a medium heat, with 1 large sprig fresh thyme, for about 10 mins stirring often, until you have a softened mixture.

STEP 5
Season the mushroom mixture, pour over 100ml dry white wine and cook for about 10 mins until all the wine has been absorbed. The mixture should hold its shape when stirred.

STEP 6
Remove the mushroom duxelle from the pan to cool and discard the thyme.

STEP 7
Overlap two pieces of cling film over a large chopping board. Lay 12 slices prosciutto on the cling film, slightly overlapping, in a double row.

STEP 8
Spread half the duxelles over the prosciutto, then sit the fillet on it and spread the remaining duxelles over.

STEP 9
Use the cling filmâ€™s edges to draw the prosciutto around the fillet, then roll it into a sausage shape, twisting the ends of cling film to tighten it as you go.

STEP 10
Chill the fillet while you roll out the pastry.

STEP 11
Dust your work surface with a little flour. Roll out a third of the 500g pack of puff pastry to a 18 x 30cm strip and place on a non-stick baking sheet.

STEP 12
Roll out the remainder of the 500g pack of puff pastry to about 28 x 36cm.

STEP 13
Unravel the fillet from the cling film and sit it in the centre of the smaller strip of pastry.

STEP 14
Beat the 2 egg yolks with 1 tsp water and brush the pastryâ€™s edges, and the top and sides of the wrapped fillet.

STEP 15
Using a rolling pin, carefully lift and drape the larger piece of pastry over the fillet, pressing well into the sides.

STEP 16
Trim the joins to about a 4cm rim. Seal the rim with the edge of a fork or spoon handle.

STEP 17
Glaze all over with more egg yolk and, using the back of a knife, mark the beef Wellington with long diagonal lines taking care not to cut into the pastry.

STEP 18
Chill for at least 30 mins and up to 24 hrs. Heat oven to 200C/fan 180C/gas 6.

STEP 19
Brush the Wellington with a little more egg yolk and cook until golden and crisp â€“ 20-25 mins for medium-rare beef, 30 mins for medium. Allow to stand for 10 mins before serving in thick slices.

Originally the game interested me because I just love climbing on structures in video games, but Only Up! Is so much more than this. 
Iâ€™m still fascinated by the different areas you pass through on your way to the top and the creativity that has flown into it, it felt like there was a good amount of thought behind everything. 
And there is also a crazy speedrun route that somehow works if you are into that. 
  
As much fun I had with the game thou, you need some frustration resistance, since one bad jump can send you a long long way down again. 
But each time, you make it back up quicker and learn from your earlier mistake, and this motivated me go climb back more than it frustrated me.  
What is also good to know I think is, that there is no save option. If you quit, you are back to the start. 

If you, who is reading this right now, ever had to urge to climb on things in games, or just tried to see if it was possible, then Only Up! is a game I can fully recommend to you

this game has serious optimization issue

I love parkour, and while the controls are really weird, the gameplay was a lot of fun to me. 

However that's where the positives end. The entire game feels like a cheap collection of default assets glued together in Unreal Engine or something, with little to no effort. There seems to be no obvious way to remap keys, the sound slider doesn't affect all sounds (wind volume is fixed apparently), UI is a collection of uninspired buttons and low quality png images, and the sound my pc made leads me to believe this game is very poorly optimised.

In a world where the competitors for this type of game are Getting Over It (with its inspired and witty voice over, unusual gameplay, original environments from the first 20 minutes, etc) and Jump King (also with unusual gameplay, genuine pixel art, etc), this game feels like a cheap copy of Getting Over It's concept made with no effort at all, using default and stolen 3D models, and with an uninspired and unemotional TTS voice over that makes it feel like the devs didn't care enough to hire a voice actor, or even voice it themselves, or even write a good script.

Once the TTS started telling parts of the story in the most monotone way, I couldn't go on anymore. The effort put into this game is in no way worth 7â‚¬, let alone 10â‚¬, when Getting Over It is barely a fifth of the price for an amount of effort orders of magnitude greater..

honestly, aside from that one part, I quite enjoyed the game and the experience. I hope that more games like this come out. it's a great balance between being challenging but having a good amount of progression.

The idea of the game is not bad, but how it was created is simply dramatic. This game is not optimized at all. I couldn't even start the "second part" because my fps dropped to zero and it was impossible to play (I was already playing on the lowest options). Other things I didn't like were that the first-person camera isn't centered inside the head, but slightly in front, and when the body rotates, it doesn't rotate in the middle of the body, but slightly to the side. Running is also strange because when you run, the ground acts like ice. Climbing is also strange. I've climbed millions of times on things I didn't even want to climb on and when I want to climb on something character didn't want to.

I hated the game at first, because of the super clunky physics, movement, and hit-box. I swear there were so many unfair falls that I shouldn't have fell. But I just wanted to beat this damn annoying game once in for all, and I did. To be honest, I consider this game as testing your patience more, rather than testing your skill, like Getting over it or Jump King. I think if you don't give up, you are most likely going to beat the game no matter what. It just takes a long, LONG time to.

I also really liked the world view of the game. This dystopian city and a little bit of dark backstory were really interesting. Maybe it's because I commonly like B-games such as Getting over it and Sexy Hiking.

I know this sounds exaggerated and ridiculous, but maybe beating this game kind of encouraged me to never give up, even though it might seem impossible, just like when I looked up and saw the endless-looking way to go, and when i tried speedrunning a couple times, it actually gradually became easier and easier to beat it, everytime a bit faster than before (final time, 19:32)

I'd maybe recommend this game if you legitimately want to beat the game, but not really if you just want to casually run around without the intention of beating it. I think the true satisfaction and charm of this game hides behind after beating it, or else it will just bring you frustration.

Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field, always looking up!

Only Up is a good game! It is a very good game. But it has a lot of glitches to fix, and more exploring opportunity needs to be considered. The thing that separates this game from Get Over It, is the fact that you have more scenery and you can take your time and appreciate the effort it took to build it all. In some ways its easier then Get Over It because your character can actually do more with interacting with the environment. They can jump, run, and balance. Which I say again opens more opportunity for exploration. Different towers to climb, even caves that you could explore that would be on the side. Finding hidden shot cuts to by pass other obstacles you've already experienced was a good idea. But making it a little less choppy and a little more smooth would help a lot. Especially with the tighter turns and corners that you have to squeeze your character through. Just for fun I was thinking, what if you could actually interact with the other people that you find. Not much of a difference but being able to click on them and having a bubble pop up over them and say something. That's just a thought though, I feel this game has a lot of potential. I say run with it! :)

Don't know how many people are going to actually read this review, but I'll try to explain.

I hated the game at first, because of the super clunky physics, movement, and hit-box. I swear there were so many unfair falls that I shouldn't have fell. But I just wanted to beat this damn annoying game once in for all, and I did. To be honest, I consider this game as testing your patience more, rather than testing your skill, like Getting over it or Jump King. I think if you don't give up, you are most likely going to beat the game no matter what. It just takes a long, LONG time to.

I also really liked the world view of the game. This dystopian city and a little bit of dark backstory were really interesting. Maybe it's because I commonly like B-games such as Getting over it and Sexy Hiking.

I know this sounds exaggerated and ridiculous, but maybe beating this game kind of encouraged me to never give up, even though it might seem impossible, just like when I looked up and saw the endless-looking way to go.

I'd maybe recommend this game if you legitimately want to beat the game, but not really if you just want to casually run around without the intention of beating it. I think the true satisfaction and charm of this game hides behind after beating it, or else it will just bring you frustration.

I'm sorry if my English was weird, English is not my first language. Thanks for reading this long random ass dude's speech. Hope you can beat the game if you get it.

On first launch it doesn't work on the RX 7900 XTX, so you need to read community posts first and then find out that their DX12 implementation doesn't work with this GPU and that you need to add -DX11 to the launch options.

Optimisation also is a bit lacking in certain areas, needs some updates and fixes.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

This game saved my life.

I am 50.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiraling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

A game that can be beat in 30 seconds if exploited.

Only Up! is a game that rides the wave of streamer popularity but falls short of its potential. Inspired by Getting Over It, it offers a frustrating experience with little polish. The repetitive and poorly delivered text-to-speech dialogue detracts from any intended inspiration but that's to to be expected from a parody game. The game's visuals and mechanics are basic but functional, and the straightforward pathways make progress easy at times. However, it feels rushed and lacks the depth of a well-developed game. 

This is a game truly made for content creators, there isn't any replayability but I recommend this game for those seeking a difficult platform challenge.

Do you like to punish yourself? Do you like beating a game in only one sitting and no more? well is this the game for you!!! Around every turn is the chance to destroy your mental well being and every bit of progress you have made and start over from scratch no mater how far you've made it so far. Is it agonizing? Yes. is it detrimental to my mental health? Yes. Would I purchase it again? Totally. Game has good mechanics for being what it is and it also has a very hard completion path that will show you tons of Easter eggs and short cuts as you replay the same section 124 times. Tear jerking, heart wrenching, and soul crushing with a tinge of hope lingering at the end of an EXTREMELY LONG tunnel.

I'm not very good at 3d games and I'm a controller guy not a keyboard and mouse guy. That being said, I really enjoy playing this game. You CAN play with a generic gamepad, but you have to set your sensativity every time you start a run. It doesn't remember any settings. There are no saves. There is an elevator that slowly moves you to  the midpoint of the game that you can jump off at any point for practice now, which is nice. This game is also super fun to watch others stream and speedrun. Get ready to fall and get mad, but you'll keep coming back!

Saw the game online, thought i'd give it a go. Just a boring version of Getting Over It imo. For me, it didn't scratch the same itch Getting Over It did, as GOI instantly hooked me with it's interesting movement and visuals. Only Up accomplishes its goals in the visual department, but the gameplay never felt fun or good. It felt too rewarding, and too finicky in the wrong ways. I had so much control over my character, that the only time I fell was when I landed on an object that slid me off of it.

I'm not sure if there will be a true successor to GOI, but this isn't it for me.

I first thought the game was just about climbing up, but the game actually presents a story about the character. The game teaches you to overcome obstacles by trying over and over, even if you fall to the bottom. I like the fact that the game has no save and quit feature. It forces you to put in more work to learn the mechanics and parts of the game so that you can beat it in one sitting. (Once you beat the game you will have likely played many parts over and it basically becomes muscle memory). This game definitely takes some mental strength to beat and I think it can actually teach players a very important lesson.

It's the buggiest game EVER. You run straight in a staircase and suddenly your character turns to a side... You jump 1000 thousands times in one spot and ALWAYS grab the edge, but now the game decides to not grab this time... Bro, the idea is AMAZING but now is not worthy. I have just finished the game in 86 minutes. The sad part is the best way to win the game is not going through the game (because of the bugs). The best way is taking as many skips as possible. The idea should be the exact opposite: Going through ALL the paths enjoying every single one.

I don't mind the janky controls, how punishing the game is or the lack of respawn checkpoints. The game is still fun in spite of these quirks. But a very basic omission prevents me from recommending it: a 'Save and Exit' feature. The game is simply too long to complete in a single sitting for the average player. If I want to stop playing for the night and pick it up the following day, there is no other option except to start from the very beginning, which is beyond frustrating. I've yet to see the upper half of the map because I don't want to keep playing forever or leave the game running in the background and sap memory. Once the developer adds this feature I will gladly pick it up again; until then I can't stomach the early grind anymore.

Dear SCKR Games,

I hope this message finds you well. I recently purchased your game, Only Up, and I must say, I am thoroughly impressed with the concept and gameplay. The vibrant visuals and engaging mechanics have truly captured my attention. However, upon trying to install the game on my Mac, I discovered that it is currently only available for Windows.

As an avid Mac user, I was disappointed to learn that I would be unable to enjoy Only Up on my preferred platform. I wanted to reach out to you today to kindly request that you consider adding Mac support to your game. By expanding the game's compatibility to include macOS, you would not only make it accessible to a wider audience but also potentially boost sales.

Mac users, like myself, represent a significant portion of the gaming community, and catering to their needs would certainly attract more players. Additionally, the Mac market is known for its strong demand for quality games, making it a promising opportunity to tap into.

By enabling Mac users to experience Only Up, you would open up new avenues for your game's success. The addition of Mac support could help garner positive reviews, word-of-mouth recommendations, and ultimately lead to increased sales and popularity.

I understand that developing and optimizing a game for multiple platforms can be challenging and time-consuming. However, I believe that the effort invested in bringing Only Up to Mac users would be worthwhile, not only for myself but for a growing number of gamers who enjoy playing on macOS.

Thank you for considering my request. I eagerly look forward to your response and the possibility of experiencing Only Up on my Mac. Your dedication to expanding the game's availability would undoubtedly be greatly appreciated by the Mac gaming community.

Wishing you continued success and hoping for a positive outcome,

Mikosh

This game feels AI generated, to be honest.

The graphics are sometimes borderline unsettling, the dialogue is strange, not needed, and voice-to-text, and most of all...a complete waste of time and money.

I was excited to play this since I've always been a huge fan of parkour games. I was flying through the level and questioned if all the online content creators I've watched play the game were failing or making it tougher for content sake and leaning into the game being trendy currently. I jumped on a completely large and solid ground and the character went straight through it and fell down the very bottom. For the record, I still think people are making this game seem impossible just for content sake.

I'm not sure how that's funny or fun in any capacity. I don't play games for the "meme." I play games because I want to enjoy them. Once it escapes being trendy online to content creators, it will quickly disappear into the "Hey, do you remember" category forever. I'm certain of that.

I issued a refund and have no interest in ever revisiting this game in the future.

This game is terrible. Yeah, there are fun aspects, the idea itself is incredible, the environment looks amazing and the controls feel pretty good, not much delay or anything like it.

BUT!!

Everything falls apart very quickly into the game when you realize how poor it's made. I'm just gonna explain what I experienced bad that made me to say a big NO NO to this game.

The same model of an object you're jumping on can feel different every time. Sometimes I was able to easily climb something and on another identical object, my character just refused to climb it and I fell.
There are textures that just throw you off when you jump on them for no logical reason, you just slide on them and fall.
There are textures that have no collision at all, I fell on an object and I wanted to reposition myself under a tree, I jumped on the ground near the tree and I simply fell through it because that texture had no collision. 

And many more.

I totally understand that this game should be frustrating, but there is a difference between a truly challenging game (this game is actually not hard if you are patient and you focus enough, I finished it in 4 hours) and a game sold under the "challenging" umbrella, but it's just made so poor, that it becomes challenging. 
I do not mind challenging games, but I want to be punished only when I make mistakes. I do not consider normal to be punished for an event where I literally had no choice.

If you are truly a masochist, you can go on and play this game, it's gonna make you question your life choices, but sadly, not because it's challenging, but because it's bad.

GL climbing!
