Das Spiel ist Ã¤hnlich zu einem anderen Spiel nÃ¤mlich AltF4, auf welches ich mich auch beziehen werde als Beispiel, da es die meisten bereits kennen, um das Spiel in einen Wort zu beschreiben wÃ¼rde ich Interessant sagen, aber mehr gibts unten.

Schwierigkeit:
In AltF4 gab es mehr "zufÃ¤llige Dinge" die passiert sind wie z.B. Fische,Kanone oder Schweine die in dich rein geflogen sind, es gab also einerseits Einfluss vom Spieler aber auch vom Spiel. In diesem Spiel hast du wenn Ã¼berhaupt Plattformen die runter fallen wenn du drauf springst, heiÃŸt nach dem ersten mal weiÃŸt du wo welche "Fallen" sind. Abgesehen davon sind die beiden Ã¼brigen GrÃ¼nde, weswegen man runter fallen kÃ¶nnte, die folgenden: entweder ist man zu gierig und springt vorbei ("skill issue") oder der Charakter meint sich nicht an eine Kante ranzuhÃ¤ngen.

Negativ:
Und da kommen wir auch zum Hauptpunkt weswegen das Spiel mich negativ stimmt. Es kann nicht sein, dass das Spiel Erlebnis behindert wird, durch Bugs und es passiert nicht nur ein,zwei mal sondern sehr oft das der Char sich nicht an eine Kante eines Objektes dranhÃ¤ngt, obwohl man hoch genug ist und die Hitbox offensichtlicher weise berÃ¼hrt. Allgemein sind Hitboxen eher hingeklatscht obwohl sie das Spiel ausmachen. So sind die Schachfiguren, Treppen und weitere Stellen so komisch, dass der Char runterrutscht. WÃ¤re dieser Makel nicht da, (wobei ich mir auch vorstellen kÃ¶nnte das es extra ist) kÃ¶nnte man nur noch an skill issue scheitern und das Spiel wÃ¤re um einiges einfacher als AltF4.

Positiv:
Das Spiel bietet eine schÃ¶ne und entspannte Musik zwischendurch. Die Musik die kommt wenn man runterfÃ¤llt wÃ¼rde ich auch eher als amÃ¼sant bezeichnen im Zusammenhang mit der Synchronsprecherin obwohl die schon echt nervig ist, da sie extra provokant sein soll und ich daher eher als lustig auffasse. If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

This entire game is made for shilling out NFTs. The clothes your character wears, the art on all the walls, it's all Goblintown NFT shilling. *There is one or more NFTs on screen at all times.*

Edit: I have since also learned that a large chunk of the assets in this game were stolen from other games, and even some solo 3D artists. 

This game was made for the sole purpose of passively advertising NFTs through unknowing streamers; This is the only game this developer has ever put out, and it's a lazy asset flip with TTS narration, packed with stolen work, all so that they could fill it to the brim with Goblin Town NFTs and logos. Not a great look for their one and only release, and not something I will be supporting after learning this.

Overall, interesting concept with much more work to be done to earn a recommendation. There are differences between game mechanics being complex, difficult, and broken. The major pro to Only Up! is that it offers a great range of difficult and complex puzzles to navigate. What ultimately does in my recommendation is the broken grab and camera mechanics. Sometimes the player grabs onto obstacles even when you think it wont. Other times, during critical obstacles or jumps, the grab mechanic just 'breaks' and the animation fails to work correctly. Thus, 20-30+ minutes can be ruined; not by player error but straight up the game not working correctly. Until this critical piece is fixed, no one should be paying for this game.

I like the game, even though it screams "lazy" all over and has a ton of bugs. I just like going up I guess. 
However, I can't recommend this game currently because there is no progression saving. So when playing an hour of going up, and then for whatever reason needing to take a break and exiting the game, you lose all your progress. This for me is a no go. I can't have a game that requires me to put in set amount of hours to beat the game in one sitting only because otherwise i lose all that i have gained. That is insanity. I don't mind losing progress due to falling back down by my own mistakes, but when a simple break from the game becomes a full reset, that is where i draw the line.

So until a update comes where progression saving is added, i am refunding the game.

We all enjoy games differently and this game here is a good one that a lot of us want to enjoy. Just some of us have different experiences when it comes to "fun". I would 100% still be playing this right now if there was a checkpoint feature, but after falling a few times I can't do it. I will leave the game installed and not refund just because I'm holding out for hope that this gets implemented in the future. 

Overall, a cool game and fun idea. The developer is responsive and making updates. I'll leave it installed and hang tight for the updates.

The only reason this game gets NEGATIVE reviews is because they can't beat it. Nowadays everyone is so used to play games that are easy with infinite restarts and checkpoints where you continue playing from the exact spot you just failed. Giving you infinite number of tries at no cost and no worries to fail while in Only Up! you don't get that luxury. In here, if you do mess up, you might end up losing hours of progress. And if you're lucky, a quick thinker with good reaction you just might not fall all the way down.

Yes. The movement is not perfect and is a bit clunky and weird at times. For example you will go through stairs and then you won't be able to pass 1 stair step and you have to jump that one stair to keep going even though it looks like a normal staircase. Yes sometimes if you don't jump perfectly and not touch the hitbox from its right angle it will not grab and you will fall. But to me, this makes the game what it is. It makes it difficult and keeps you focused. If it was too smooth and every jump would just connect then this game would lose its sweetness. It's a 10$ game. Don't expect it to be too perfect. I like it because it is the way it is. Its flaws make it a good thing.

Only Up! gives you an experience you'll never forget.

It's Happy. It's Sad. It's Scary.

It's happy: with objects like: Ice Cream, Strawberries, Macrons, Oreo's, Skateboards, a Tetris and MANY MORE! I won't write them all as there's hundreds. But i really have to mention the unexpected Turkish SAZ instrument at the end and the Tuong ot spiracha Chilly Sauce (My Favorite) was very surprising and exciting to see in game. Thank you for that. Oh hey.. Did i mention there's a condom in the sky?

It's Sad: with the story and his father. And along the way you will be told to go back. You will fail. You won't make it. You're a weak kid. And once you're back in the beginning. After being so high up in the sky. You will see even a smaller kid than you looking up in the sky dreaming about going there while you just came back.

It's Scary: because you have high adrenaline while playing and you have the fear of not falling because if you fall you might have to do everything all over again! There is this part where your screen gets black & white and you see creepy stuff with creepy music and sounds on the background. It was really creepy.

I loved this game. It will really test your patience and your skills. It has shortcuts and is perfect for Speed Running as well. You can try to play as safely as you can. Or you can run and make long risky jumps to get through objects faster and skip some content to finish the game faster. Only Up! Is an amazing game and it has really cool game developers. Their vision is just beautiful.

I wish there was Controller Support :( . I'm looking forward to Night Mode and Multiplayer! Multiplayer is gonna be AMAZING!!!

Believing in yourself is half the battle. You fell? GO AGAIN! You made it once you'll make it again!
the game is good  but the fck iii n   g trolls s s at the end  and if u fall down you dont want to do this shit again

All memes aside, the game is frustrating but fun. I will address the two most important things people complain about:

1. "The game doesn't have saving" - Now some people refer to a checkpoint system, which honestly I think would ruin the game, the whole scary tension part is knowing at any time you could fall right back to beginning. While others refer to the fact that the game should save your position when you exit, this point is valid (especially since the game can crash and you will lose all progress), however, the game is short enough to where I think this can be overlooked, I beat the game in 8 hours across three different sittings, with my last attempt lasting 2hrs 30mins.

2. "The mechanics are clunky" - Whether by design or not, I think the clunky mechanics add to the difficulty of the game, in a similar way to how the annoying hammer in getting over it feels clunky. I think the game plays fine, especially after the last update, they improved the vaulting and falling mechanics a bit. You will get used to how the character handles relatively quickly.

Now as far as actual criticisms go, my only one is related to the cheesy traps. There are a few points in the game where you will land on something, just to have it instantly fall and reset you back to the beginning (or some other similar trap). This to me isn't good game design and just feels cheap because there are no way to tell the traps apart or even react to them, you just fall, instantly. 

Overall considering the price, I think it's worth a buy. Finishing the game is a huge satisfaction.

A fairly fun game, if you enjoyed Getting Over It or Alt F4, you should get this game. However, I can't recommend this game due to a lack of an auto save. Unless you're able to beat the game in a single sitting, exiting to the menu will have you start the game all over again. This was particularly frustrating when I closed the game about 4/5 of the way up to go to bed, only to find my progress erased the following morning. I understand the desire to avoid save scumming, but this can be avoided with a clever auto save system, while still permitting players to save their progress and pick up where they left off the next day.

1. Aesthetics-wise, this looks very very good. I like the style and setting, so that's a plus.

 2. If you're someone with anger-issues but is insistent to try it out anyway, I'd hold off until they fix some of the game's bugs. From the setting, it's apparent that this project is rather ambitious in terms of all the platforms working as intended, but it's also weird, since I've clipped through platforms during the early parts of the game that would've seemed easy to notice and patch. So, who knows, time will tell. 

3. The controls are a little tricky, but nothing you won't get used to, just be ware that the parkour / climbing mechanics aren't as polished as you'd like for them to be. 

in conclusion, wait until some patches have been... well, patched, which the devs/dev have been on top of, but it's a fun game, and frustrating at times.

Is this game fun? Yes.
Is this game frustrating? Yes.
Is it a good challenge? Yes.

Do I recommend the game? No.

The game is plagued with inconsistencies in how the character grabs ledges, sprints, and how the character interacts with the various terrain. The game also has some serious bugs one of which where god's hand that carries you to a section of the game completely broke for me and was stuck at the next place (I fell back down to god's hand). Therefore, my game was hard locked and I would have to start all over again as this game has no checkpoints.

The game also lacks a good amount of options in the settings menu and has a forced FPS cap of 90. The "sliders" for mouse sensitivity and sound are not actually silders, they have very fixed points and if you put it between 2 points it snaps to the closest one. So you are not able to set your settings properly.

Good concept, ruined by bad development.

Only played this after June 14 patch. Some people say it makes the game more responsive, others that it makes the game too easy. Personally I had fun. The game isn't as difficult as Getting Over It or Jump King, but it is also considerably longer, giving you more room to screw up and fall. It took me exactly 3 hours to beat my first climb, but that was with only one fall that cost me about 15 minutes, and I feel there's plenty of other things to find while exploring, so I'm probably gonna play it again.

As for the bad, the game feels a bit rough around the edges, trampolines can throw you in hard to predict directions, causing you to fall, and few times I got temporarily stuck on geometry. Voice acting is pretty bad as well, but I guess it's suppose to be parody or something. Also with the game being as long as it is, it's really unfortunate that there's no save on exit function.

The most recent update makes the game playable. With a centered camera and less buggy collisions on rounded surfaces, most of these reviews have been made obsolete (press 1 to get a sane camera where forward is forward btw). 

This is a Getting Over It style game through and through (A Foddian game?), though its a more genuine take on the genre ala Jump King. Lots of insane microplatforming challenges obsoleted by more daring but easier trampoline sections; it really is a game of risk versus reward where not getting tilted is the main goal. 

My only gripe is that the game does not have autosaving, or any kind of saving to disc for that matter. I know the devs say that "not saving is part of the game", but I dont want checkpoints, I want a way to rage close the game and not lose all my progress. Dark Souls has a way to let you quit out without letting you save scum; the feature exists. Also save the settings to disc so I dont need to set it every time I open the game, and either mix the audio better or let me turn off your music while keeping your (interesting, if comically translated) voice content. The fact that the bottom of the slider isnt mute is annoying. 

Overall, I wouldnt have recommended before the update today. Now that the game is fundamentally fair though, it's been an addicting and challenging game.

A journey to be sure. No in game saving, every time you launch it you start from the very beginning. You'll climb to a new point, ready for the next section, then you'll bounce off the edge or accidentally walk right off a platform and you might fall all the way to the bottom. Of you do fall that far, luckily there is only one way to go after that.

Outstanding experience. If you like jump king, you might see this game and think its similar. While jump king has precise jumps down the the last pixel, this game is filled with risk assessment and is a test on your patience. If you just walk the whole game, and take safe jumps, you could win first try, but doing things fast and going for risky skips is very fun. People complain about the controls, but really i think they are quite good, the running speed feels fluid, there is good air strafing speed, but the "climb up" mechanic is somewhat hard to get used to. The character has a range to where he can clamber to, and to get good at the game is to feel out this range, to build up confidence in making it onto the next platform. Aside from the gameplay and mechanics, the visuals are really quite great in my opinion. Its sort of a collage of many assets and common game objects, that create a beautiful landscape that had me excited to continue the climb. To be honest, i was hesitant to use skips that a found early into my play through, just because i wanted to experience this handcrafted environment. My only real criticism of the game, is that i wish there was less bed skips. i think its fun to optimize your route through taking a riskier farther jump, but the beds(or other boosting objects) let you skip so much of the game, it would have taken me much longer to beat the game without them, and i plan to do a "no bed" run on my further replays of this game. All in all, 10/10 game for me, if you enjoyed Getting over it with Bennet Foddy, or similar games, pick this game up.

As the name indicates, this game is basically find a way up and you can only go up. You might fall down if you are not cautious which add some challenges to it. I play it for less than two hours and finally gave up. I quite enjoyed it at first since the game itself is interesting and finding a way up is both challenging and fun. 
One of the reasons I gave up: I changed my mouse sensitivity to a lower one in the setting and made sure I clicked the save button. But when I resume the game, the sensitivity remains unchanged and stays the same high sensitivity. Is this a bug or something? Has anyone encountered the same issue? I found it quite inconvenient when the sensitivity is too high and what annoys me is that I can't even change it. Every time I opens the game, the sensitivity returns to the default highest one.
Another reason is that this game has no saving button, you can't save your progress halfway and need to start from the very beginning the next time. It's quite frustrating for me not to be able to pick up from where I left of last time. So unless you spend quite some time chained to your desk play it through, you'll need to start from the beginning the next time. That's understandable some players like challenging games and the achievement it brings when you finally reach the top is very exciting. But for casual gamer like me who just want to have some fun after a day's work, starting over each time when having a minor error is frustrating. 
One suggestion I would really like to propose: Perhaps this game can have two modes, casual and normal. Casual mode is more convenient and can save progress or adding some saving points in the game, allowing players to pick up where they left of last time and can enjoy the game at their own pace. Normal mode is the current mode without saving points for those who seek challenges and want to show their skill in the speed-run.
In general though, it's a good game and I would recommend it especially for those who want to have some fun and challenges at the same time. I just hope it can gets better.  <3

It hurts me to give a bad review, but honestly, this is just a very half-hearted game. I can see that the developer wanted to create something he has fun with, a playground to test his developer-skills. But for a price of 10.99$?

Really, this is nothing more than a tech-demo, which at some point someone thought: hey, lets just add a bunch of more generic bought assets and pile it on top, so we can sell it.

If at least the camera, controls and performance were better, or it was an early-access game. i'd reconsider my review. But clunky and unresponsive controls, a camera which misleads you to where you run to (just make it a first-person camera, most issues fixed) and very very bad performance is an instant no-recommendation for me.

I'd give it a thumb up for effort, if the price was maybe 1-2 dollars. Don't judge me by my playtime: i saw videos and develop some games by myself, and i know when something is not worth my time.

I understand why there's no saving in the game. It's to heighten the stakes and tension of the climb. Tough but fair. 

However, you literally can't close the software without being sent back to the start, meaning the game needs to be beat in one sitting. Which, in turn, means the game is literally unbeatable for me. 

The game should preserve your location if you close the software, even if it doesn't want to let you save. 

Also, there are some invisible walls and floors with no physics that you fall through that make the game feel pretty unfair sometimes. These two issues combined make this game more frustration than it's worth. 

The game should be challenging but fair. Instead it's actively unfair and unbeatable on top of that.

Terribly designed and optimized game. Character movement is way too clunky for a "getting over it" style of game, which isn't even the worst of it's issues. Too many objects/props that require double/triple mounting to get over such as a pipe elbow joint.  But most importantly is the seemingly randomly placed invisible walls in paths that look like it could be a route forward, only to block you with an invisible wall which leads you into a funnel of invisible walls that brings you back to the start with no indication or chance of knowing that it was the wrong path. It punishes exploring at no fault of the player, because they were too lazy to finish out said route and just decided to block it with invisible walls and call it a day. Falling because you failed to make a jump or you tried to get cocky and take a risky route is fine, but when you fall because the player didn't develop the game and/or trial and error multiple paths until they found one that wasn't blocked by a nonsensical invisible wall, especially a path that seeming has a route, and gets blocked by something you can't see after the 3rd jump of what looks to be a path of 20+ jumps is unreasonably punishing. Either make the invisible walls visible or marked, or finish the paths.

so the author of this game, we need Chinese audio/captions. The background voices have so many design features, I'm so sad that people who don't know English well can't understand those.

Fun for a while, but stay away if youâ€™re not a fan of precision climbers where success depends on unreliable texture and mechanics.

These games have a very limited audience, which means theyâ€™re not for a regular gamer. Playing this for personal enjoyment is not advised, however it is fine for a few runs when friends are around or perhaps to entertain viewers while streaming.

Story is light and not worth mentioning. The game begins with you in the heart of the slums, where time has stood still. All living things appear to be affected by this, with the exception of birds, which took off as soon as I approached. What you do know is that you need to climb up.

Controls are simple. Despite the fact that they are available, jog and sprint are absolutely useless on narrow paths. Climbing is semi-automatic; all you have to do is jump and push into an obstacle. 

However, there is one major issue that causes unnecessary frustration. While flat surfaces are perfectly fine, every round object creates a problem for your character. When you pull yourself up on one of these things, like a pipe, you will just slide off of it.

The game tries to fix this by letting you grab and climb even if you miss a jump. As long as youâ€™re close to the platform and push forward, you will be fine. However, this doesnâ€™t work if you drop from a huge height. The surface has to be flat to save you, otherwise youâ€™ll just bounce off like itâ€™s made of rubber.

On screenshots the graphics look good and the view from above is actually quite impressive, however once you start moving, the lack of performance is brutally clear. There are clipping issues and invisible walls everywhere. In a game where one incorrect move could send you back to the ground, I had to lower the setting to get acceptable frames per second. 

The goal of the game is to reach the top. You can see a vertical route of pipes, railroad tracks, and other pieces in the sky as you gaze up. It looks like the world exploded and sent everything flying up in the air. 

What I admire about the stage is that it doesn't appear as though someone threw random pieces in the hopes that they will function. There is some sort of meaning hidden behind the path. Sometimes you can even choose between two paths.

There is some narration, but I had a hard time following it because there are no subtitles. On the other hand, this voice repeats every time you restart the climb, so you will definitely hear it the more you mess up. Also, Iâ€™m pretty sure the voice was put through an AI program because it doesnâ€™t sound natural at all.

If you didn't know, there are no shortcuts or save games in this kind of game. One run is required to complete the entire climb. Because I haven't yet reached or discovered it, I can't say for sure if there are shortcuts in this game. Thereâ€™s an elevator at the bottom and beds you can jump on, but they donâ€™t appear to offer any help.

I donâ€™t mind these games when theyâ€™re fair. Sadly, there are many situations where all your effort is erased by the gameâ€™s lack of polish.

[url=https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/2029480769577785229/5BD7AFBA1D041A968E7F0D98BF123F6BFE314811/?imw=5000&imh=5000&ima=fit&impolicy=Letterbox&imcolor=%23000000&letterbox=false]Finally I beat this game.[/url]
I won't recommend you guys reading this review to buy this game at full price. IMO, it's not really worth it, it's [b]mostly[/b] just a bunch of cheap random models stacked into the freaking high upper stratosphere. It's about bad Value For Money.
TBH, I kinda had some fun playing it. I must say, I like the idea of it which plays like some custom maps of GTA5 for the first few hours. But what I can't stand is falling or getting stuck 'casue of some stupid bugs or lags or model clippings.
Anyway, it's recommended to those who are really idle and like jumping games. It's fun to watch others fall over and over then beat it but it's suffering play by yourself.

Update(2023-06-05):
I checked those latest patches, the author shows great attitude which makes me wanna give it another shot.
But a few minutes later, I found a new bug at [url=https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/2029480769574590165/509BD899480F7DDBF92C220B007BD346E81A8120/?imw=5000&imh=5000&ima=fit&impolicy=Letterbox&imcolor=%23000000&letterbox=false]this place[/url]. I stuck between containers and I tried every direction and action, I just cannot get out.
All right, maybe give it another shot next time.

[hr][/hr]

Update(2023-05-26) recommendâ†’not recommend:
When I reached the end of the ice scene using all medium quality graphics settings(i7-7700 & GTX1066), there's a room slightly ahead of [url=https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/2030606034828331200/283088BD5E87311CEA890A6763432EF7462BDE75/?imw=5000&imh=5000&ima=fit&impolicy=Letterbox&imcolor=%23000000&letterbox=false]this place[/url]  with hollowed-out floor and half an orange floating in the air. Even I moved extremely carefully, I couldn't tell there's a trap because of the graphics setting which is limited by hardware. I just went straight ahead and then fell to somewhere very close to the ground. I figure the Contrast and the Saturation of that scene is too low at medium settings to make the player aware of the danger.
Afterwards I checked other players' videos, it turns out it's easier to distinguish that ice stick from nothing at higher settings, maybe the developers should modify those transparent grounds a lit bit to improve the game experience at lower graphics settings.

Also, things like the cuboid at the end of [url=https://steamuserimages-a.akamaihd.net/ugc/2030606034828323864/B42BC437CE89CBFE7E23FD077E6B32B284F37C67/?imw=5000&imh=5000&ima=fit&impolicy=Letterbox&imcolor=%23000000&letterbox=false]this road[/url], their actual collision volumes are smaller than their appearance, which often leads to model clipping and distance misjudging.
Besides, idk why there're no achievements in this game.

Thx for replying, but I reckon that GTX1060 is slightly better than GTX1650, mine is mobile(Laptop) though. XD

[hr][/hr]

In a word, this game is Aerial Acrobat Simulator.

We are born with only two innate fears: the fear of falling and the fear of loud sounds.
Loud creepy sounds are often used by jumpscares in most horror games. Only Up will tell you what the real horror is in the other way, it'll let you climb into the upper clouds and trick you into falling down without any checkpoints.

Btw, I love those graffiti like the Journey to the West one, those static lovely family models, the city and other scenes, and the music includes the narrator (except when I was falling D:).

A good game, very interesting ,but can your guys save my game progress when i quit or this game will be too hard to complete?
